<section class="section relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="text-center mb-8 animate-on-scroll">
            <span class="section__eyebrow">No surprises</span>
            <h2 class="mt-4 text-display font-bold text-white">Where "free" ends</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-8">
            <p class="text-gray-400">Being upfront beats a hidden paywall. Here is exactly when you pay:</p>
            <ul class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-gray-400 list-disc list-inside stagger-children--tight">
                <li class="animate-on-scroll"><strong class="text-gray-200">Self-hosted stays free forever</strong>: no license cost, no volume cap. You only pay for your own infrastructure.</li>
                <li class="animate-on-scroll"><strong class="text-gray-200">Cloud paid plans</strong> (Startup at €59/mo excl. VAT, then Pro) unlock higher volume, more applications and dedicated support. No feature is locked behind them; the free tier already has HMAC signing, retries, logs and the portal.</li>
                <li class="animate-on-scroll"><strong class="text-gray-200">Scale and support are what you pay for.</strong> If you need more than 100 events/day on the cloud, or a managed SLA, that is the paid line.</li>
            </ul>
            <div class="mt-6">
                <a href="./pricing" class="text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300 underline" onclick="trackEvent('CTA', 'Click', 'webhook-free-pricing')">See full pricing →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

<!-- FAQ Section -->
<section class="section relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute inset-0 grid-pattern opacity-20"></div>
    <div class="relative z-10 max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="text-center mb-12 animate-on-scroll">
            <span class="section__eyebrow">FAQ</span>
            <h2 class="mt-4 text-display font-bold text-white">Free webhook questions</h2>
        </div>

        <div class="space-y-6 stagger-children--tight">
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Is Hook0 really free?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">Yes, in three honest ways. play.hook0.com is a free tool to test and inspect webhooks in your browser, no account needed. The open-source server is free forever to self-host with no volume cap imposed by Hook0 (SSPL-1.0). And Hook0 Cloud has a free Developer tier: 100 events/day, no credit card, no feature gating. No bait-and-switch.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Is there a free open-source webhook server?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">Yes. Hook0 is a free, open-source webhook server under SSPL-1.0, published on GitHub and GitLab. It ships with Docker Compose and Kubernetes manifests and runs on PostgreSQL. Self-hosting is free with no license cost and no volume cap from Hook0. It is the same codebase as the cloud, with the same features.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What are the free tier limits on Hook0 Cloud?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">The free Developer tier includes 1 developer, 1 application, 10 event types, 10 subscriptions, up to 100 events/day, and 7 days of data retention. All delivery features are included: HMAC signing, retries, delivery logs and the subscriber portal. No credit card is required and the tier is free forever for side-projects.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Can I test a webhook for free without an account?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">Yes. play.hook0.com gives you a public URL to receive, inspect and replay webhook payloads directly in your browser. There is nothing to install and no signup. It is free and itself open-source.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Is self-hosting Hook0 free?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">Yes. There is no license cost and no volume cap imposed by Hook0 when you self-host. You provide the infrastructure (Docker or Kubernetes plus PostgreSQL) and get community support on Discord. Managed scaling, an uptime SLA and managed updates are the things you take on yourself when self-hosting.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What is the difference between play.hook0.com and Hook0 Cloud?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">play.hook0.com is a free tool to receive, inspect and debug webhooks that other services send you. Hook0 Cloud is the infrastructure to send signed webhooks to your own users in production, with retries, a dead letter queue and a subscriber portal. Use Play to debug, use Cloud or self-hosted to ship.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">Does the free cloud tier expire or require a credit card?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">No. The free Developer tier has no time limit and requires no credit card. It is free forever for side-projects.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="animate-on-scroll card card--glow p-6">
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-2">What happens when I exceed the free cloud tier?</h3>
                <p class="text-gray-400">Events beyond 100/day on the free tier are blocked until the next day. To send more, you upgrade to a paid plan (Startup at €59/mo excl. VAT, or Pro). Paid plans only unlock higher volume and support; no feature is locked behind them. If you want no volume cap at all, self-host the open-source server for free.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

